    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The scientific community has long been divided on the issue of IQ disparities among racial groups. The traditional view, supported by the now-discredited work of Arthur Jensen and Hans Eysenck, posits that IQ differences are largely due to genetic factors and are therefore heritable. However, this perspective has been largely discredited due to methodological flaws and the failure to control for socio-economic factors. A more nuanced view, supported by researchers such as Richard Lynn and Tatu Vanhanen, suggests that IQ differences are influenced by a combination of genetic and environmental factors, including education and nutrition.",
